    "category": "DATALAKE ARCHITECTURE",
    "niche": "Cost Optimization, Lifecycle Management, and Disaster Recovery",
    "question": "What are the architectural trade-offs of utilizing localized data compression algorithms within an ingestion pipeline to minimize network transfer costs across distinct availability zones vs. the added CPU cost incurred on the worker instances?",
    "answer": "1. Cost Trade-off: compressing files at source (e.g., using ZSTD-11) reduces cross-AZ data egress costs by up to 70%.\n\n2. CPU overhead: The compression requires substantial CPU time on worker nodes, slowing down ingestion rate. Balance this by setting a lower compression level (e.g., ZSTD-3) during ingestion, and executing higher compression levels during the background compaction phases.",
