    "answer": "Dynamic Partition Pruning occurs when a query joins a partitioned fact table with a filtered dimension table. During query planning, Spark builds an execution plan where the filter on the dimension table is evaluated first. It compiles a subquery that extracts the matching partition keys from the dimension table. This list of keys is injected as a dynamic filter on the fact table scan, allowing Spark to prune partitions of the fact table at the storage layer before reading data, cutting I/O time.",
